AN  - 743067373; 201027635
AB  - Scholarly studies of the impact of TV on political attitudes have focused almost exclusively on news & political talk shows. The assumption that political perceptions & policy positions are not affected by fictional programs is challenged. It is noted that many TV dramas draw their plots from real-life events. In addition, those who primarily watch fictional programming tend not to be as informed, partisan, or politically involved as heavy viewers of news/political shows. An experimental design was used to test the hypothesis that narratives suggesting a favorable/unfavorable depiction of some target will influence political attitudes in a certain direction. Data were obtained between January 12, 2005 & January 11, 2006 from questionnaires completed by 86 adults (not students) before & after watching one of two episodes of "Law & Order" that presented a positive & a negative portrayal of the criminal justice system respectively. The methodology is described. The results confirmed that fictional content affect a viewer's political attitude & policy positions. Suggestions are made for future research. Figures, References. J. Lindroth
